metadata.title: Beechcraft Super King Air
aws::graph::propositions: Military Variants of Beechcraft Super King Air Model 300
One special Beechcraft Super King Air B300C variant was built for the Swiss Air Force.
The special Beechcraft Super King Air B300C variant had a modified belly to allow for aerial photography.
The special Beechcraft Super King Air B300C variant had a large observation window in the right side aft fuselage.
The special Beechcraft Super King Air B300C variant was given a construction number with a different prefix to other B300Cs.
Hawker Pacific is an aviation company in Australia.
Hawker Pacific purchased eight Beechcraft Super King Air B300s between 2003 and 2005.
Hawker Pacific purchased the eight B300s for lease to the Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF).
The eight B300s were modified as navigator trainers for the RAAF.
Hawker Pacific later leased another three Beechcraft Super King Air B300s to the Australian Army.
The three B300s leased to the Australian Army replaced B200 and B200C Model King Airs.
The Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF) has utilized King Air 350 Special Mission as an interim replacement for the DHC-4 Caribou transports.
The DHC-4 Caribou transports were from No. 38 Squadron.
The RAAF now operates 16 Beechcraft Super King Air aircraft.
The 16 Beechcraft Super King Air aircraft are operated from both No. 32 Squadron and No. 38 Squadron.

text:
#### Model 300 military variants

One special Super King Air B300C variant was built for the Swiss Air Force, with a modified belly to allow for aerial photography and a large observation window in the right side aft fuselage; and given a c/no. with a different prefix to other B300Cs.
The Hawker Pacific aviation company of Australia purchased eight B300s between 2003 and 2005 for lease to the Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF), which were subsequently modified as navigator trainers. Hawker Pacific later leased another three B300s to the Australian Army, replacing B200 and B200C Model King Airs. The RAAF has also utilized King Air 350 Special Mission as an interim replacement for the DHC-4 Caribou transports of No. 38 Squadron. The RAAF now operates 16 aircraft from both No. 32 Squadron and No. 38 Squadron.
